image.altText: Masked delivery driver in a car with a bag of takeaway food.

props.synopsis: The Fair Work Commission will have new powers to set minimum standards for rideshare and food delivery drivers under new legislation that will be voted on today.

title.children: Gig workers to benefit from minimum standards as government secures support for IR reforms

image.altText: Dutton chuckles as he points at Albanese across the dispatch box

props.synopsis: Dutton may not have produced much policy detail in the 21 months since the last election, but he's talking a big game about what's to come, writes David Speers.

title.children: Dutton took the 'least bad option' — and now his election plan is coming into view

image.altText: Australian PM Anthony Albanese and James Marape, PNG PM shake hands like lifelong friends

props.synopsis: Papua New Guinea's Prime Minister James Marape will make history as the first Pacific Island leader to deliver a speech to federal parliament. Follow live.

title.children: PNG prime minister to make historic address to parliament, new workplace laws to be passed

liveBlogKeyEvents.title: Marape is being officially welcomed in Canberra
New workplace laws to be passed today
Papua New Guinea PM to address parliament

image.altText: Unidentified image of two police officers in uniform

props.synopsis: A police officer facing rape and assault charges is committed to stand trial in the Northern Territory Supreme Court, with a local court judge finding there is "sufficient evidence" against him.

title.children: NT police officer faces Supreme Court trial on rape, choking and aggravated assault charges

image.altText: A woman smiles at the camera, in front of her are two happy kids in Ludmilla Primary uniforms.

props.synopsis: The NT government has committed to rolling out a specialist mental health education framework in all of its schools from next year. Tailored to the needs of territory kids, teachers and principals say it helps support the "emotional wellbeing" of students.

title.children: At this NT school, students are learning to stand up to bullies and be a good friend

image.altText: An aerial image of a port on the coast of the Gulf of Carpentaria near Borroloola.

props.synopsis: The High Court rules in favour of native title holders in the Northern Territory preventing mining giant Glencore from expanding a critical part of its large zinc and lead mine on the Gulf of Carpentaria.

title.children: Mining giant blocked from port expansion in High Court win for native title holders

image.altText: Blurred man in background refuses glass of whiskey

props.synopsis: February is here, and Dr Sandro Demaio has joined thousands of Aussies to hit pause on a habit in his life — drinking alcohol. This is why.

title.children: Thinking about giving up alcohol? Even a few weeks off the booze will have noticeable effects

image.altText: A woman with long black hair sitting on a light blue couch

props.synopsis: Many online have lambasted Poonam Pandey for her fake death while attempting to raise awareness for cervical cancer. But some women say she shocked people enough to make them talk about the disease and even consider getting tested.

title.children: In India, cervical cancer can be associated with 'promiscuity', making it hard for women to talk about. Did a publicity stunt change this?

image.altText: Three frames of a woman, the third a jogger.

props.synopsis: Ballarat locals are continuing to support emergency services in their efforts to locate missing woman Samantha Murphy, with Victoria Police requesting people to review any of their own CCTV footage of the area from February 4.

title.children: Search for Samantha Murphy continues as Victoria Police release CCTV footage of her running

image.altText: A doctor holds a stethoscope in two clasped hands

props.synopsis: Australia's medical regulation system claims to prioritise public safety, but often falls short of public expectations. That might be about to change.

title.children: Dramatic reform could be coming to let patients know of doctor misconduct

image.altText: A female student completes her exam using a laptop.

props.synopsis: Academic experts will be recruited to draft and proofread VCE exams in an attempt to improve quality control after repeated mistakes.

title.children: Victoria to call in experts to help proofread VCE exams after 'traumatic' errors

image.altText: Taylor Swift performs during "The Eras Tour".

props.synopsis: Swift's lawyers say the tracking tips off the superstar's stalkers while creator Jack Sweeney argues it allows transparency.

title.children: Taylor Swift sends cease and desist to college student using public information to track her private jet

image.altText: Prince William wearing a dark suit looks way from the camera as he talks with Prince Harry dressed in a dark suit.

props.synopsis: The announcement of the king's cancer diagnosis sparked immediate speculation it could be a catalyst to heal family tensions, but royal experts say the rift between the royal brothers is "more entrenched".

title.children: Charles's cancer diagnosis draws hopes of reconciliation between William and Harry

image.altText: A man looks at stock prices through the window of the ASX in Sydney.

props.synopsis: Australian stocks are poised for a muted open despite a strong session on Wall Street, while a raft of companies including AGL Energy, Charter Hall, Mirvac, News Corp and Unibail-Rodamco-Wesfield are releasing their earnings. Follow the latest updates in our live blog.

title.children: ASX set for muted open, global stocks climb to over two-year high

liveBlogKeyEvents.title: Price gouging is pushing up inflation, major report finds
Gig workers to benefit from minimum standards

image.altText: People walk past an Optus store in Sydney.

props.synopsis: Telecommunications consumers lodged 14,671 complaints between October and December 2023, an increase of more than 13 per cent compared with the previous quarter.

title.children: Optus outage caused spike of more than 900 complaints to telecommunications watchdog

image.altText: A Woolworths sign next to a Coles sign outside the shops

props.synopsis: The former chair of the ACCC takes aim at electricity providers, banks, airlines, supermarkets, and other big businesses in his new report on price gouging and unfair pricing practices.

title.children: Price gouging report finds big businesses are exploiting Australians

image.altText: A group of mourning women sit on a bench as others examine shrouded bodies.

props.synopsis: Benjamin Netanyahu has rejected a Hamas ceasefire deal that would ensure the return of hostages still held in Gaza.

title.children: Israel's prime minister rejects Hamas ceasefire proposal insisting on 'absolute victory' for Israel

image.altText: Two cruise ships sailing on blue waters and another ship nearby

props.synopsis: Cruises through the Red Sea and Suez Canal are being cancelled amid escalating conflict in the Middle East. A consumer rights lawyer says there are important things tourists should know.

title.children: How the Israel-Gaza conflict is impacting cruise ships in the Red Sea

image.altText: Lady holding a wallet with 20-dollar notes

props.synopsis: Millions of Australians face ever-increasing monthly and yearly bills and, increasingly, they are related to services many deem necessary.

title.children: 'It causes family stress and tension': Price gouging inquiries abound but the cost-of-living crisis is here and now

image.altText: Girl on a sunbed

props.synopsis: Advertisements for collarium sun bed sessions are popping up across the country, but an expert says "there is absolutely no doubt that collariums are in fact solariums" that have been banned in Australia since 2015.

title.children: Skin cancer experts urge authorities to crack down on sun beds 'rebranded' as collariums

image.altText: Farmer sitting on a tractor in a field with cattle behind him.

props.synopsis: Ambitious climate targets are super-charging the race towards renewables in regional Australia, but in many communities, the pace and scale of change is causing anxiety and uncertainty.

title.children: 'Destroying the village to save the village': Why farmers like Grant are leading the renewables resistance

image.altText: Headshot of a young man with a moustache wearing prison greens.

props.synopsis: Kingsley Pickett, who killed pregnant mother Margaret Blurton and her baby son in a 1991 high-speed crash and earned a reputation as WA's worst serial offender, is being released on a supervision order.

title.children: Killer rapist who took lives of pregnant mum and toddler son set to be freed from jail

image.altText: A pilot stands beside heavily-armed rebels in Papua.

props.synopsis: A rebel group in Indonesia's eastern region of Papua orders its armed faction deep in the jungle to release a New Zealand pilot held hostage for the past year.

title.children: West Papua rebel group orders armed faction to release kidnapped NZ pilot

image.altText: A neon sign shaped in the words Wholesale & Retail and a cannabis flower outside a shop window

props.synopsis: After Thailand decriminalised the sale of marijuana for recreational use in 2022, weed dispensaries have exploded around the country, but already the future of this industry is up in the air.

title.children: Thailand was the first country in Asia to decriminalise cannabis. A year later, it's having second thoughts

image.altText: a sign of Caxton Legal Centre

props.synopsis: Around 180,000 people were helped by Australia's community legal centres last year — but even more people were turned away from the service.

title.children: Community legal centre turning away more people than it can help due to massive demand

image.altText: Ryan Milgate standing in a paddock of crop

props.synopsis: Farmers consider running the gauntlet and leaving machinery uninsured as premiums go through the roof, with insurers blaming erratic weather, inflation, and increasing costs for the price hikes.

title.children: Farmers hit with $100,000 insurance bills as extreme weather events become more frequent

image.altText: An old photo with one man highlighted.

props.synopsis: His nickname was 'Hitler'; now former attendees of a Catholic boys school have received a letter telling them a school building has been renamed after a review into the teacher's conduct. Some of them have told the ABC what they endured.

title.children: Mr Hamilton's use of the strap was called 'sadistic'. His name has now been removed from a private school

image.altText: A close up of a person's hands, one holding an iPhone and one holding a small flip phone.

props.synopsis: With mobile phone use on the rise, some people are turning to simpler devices to help them cut down on their screen time.

title.children: Sick of doomscrolling and being 'constantly on call', these Australians switched to a 'dumbphone'

image.altText: Australian Opposition Leader Peter Dutton speaks during a press conference.

props.synopsis: Opposition Leader Peter Dutton says Prime Minister Anthony Albanese has "trashed his reputation" for a political fix, by reneging on his commitment to the stage 3 tax cuts.

title.children: Dutton says Albanese 'trashed his reputation' with tax cuts change

image.altText: John sitting on his porch with his back against a brick wall, looking very stoic.

props.synopsis: A messy zoning dispute in Williamstown in Melbourne's industrial west has led to dozens of residents being ordered to evict their residents in a campaign referred to by local council officers as "Operation Pegasus".

title.children: Residents of Techno Park say the local council 'enabled' their community. Now it wants to evict them

image.altText: A woman with her back to the camera walking next to a plain-clothed police detective.

props.synopsis: Police will allege that toddler Diana Jane Hanbury was denied medical intervention from her parents which caused her death in north Queensland in 2022.

title.children: Parents of two-year-old girl charged with murder

image.altText: A young woman and a man smile for a selfie while sitting in a car.

props.synopsis: Melissa Oates says she heard a "bang" and "panicked", but insists she had no idea she had struck her partner with her vehicle at high speed while he walked home late at night. But an inquest into Jari Wise's 2020 death has heard evidence at odds with her account.

title.children: 'I just panicked': Woman tells inquest she had no idea she had hit and killed partner with car

image.altText: Hands holding a stamped passport.

props.synopsis: The Passport Office will overhaul its passport application processes after an audit finds it knew there would be a surge in demand for passports after the pandemic, and should have planned for it.

title.children: Passport Office mismanaged 'pent up demand' for travel documents, audit finds

image.altText: the facade of a building covered in thick black smoke with three orange flames coming out of windows

props.synopsis: Strikes during the morning rush hour hit residential buildings and infrastructure, leaving many wounded and at least five dead.

title.children: Russian missile strikes on Ukrainian cities kill five, officials say

image.altText: Police examine the site of a bomb blast with debris scattered around.

props.synopsis: Two blasts near the offices of electoral candidates in Pakistan's south-west have killed dozens of people and injured many more, raising concerns about security in the lead-up to today's national election.

title.children: Dozens killed in blasts near Pakistan electoral candidates' offices on eve of election
